To increase the spark.driver.maxResultSize configuration in a Spark application¶

In [5]:
sc = spark.sparkContext
print('Original spark.driver.maxResultSize: ' + sc._conf.get('spark.driver.maxResultSize'))

# Stop existing Spark environment
sc.stop()

# Waiting for the environment to stop
sleep_time = 20
print(f'Waiting for {sleep_time} seconds for the enviroment to stop...')
time.sleep(sleep_time)

# Applying new configuration and restarting Spark
/gateway/default/node/conf?host&port = pyspark.SparkConf().setAll([('spark.driver.maxResultSize', '6g')])
sc = pyspark.SparkContext(/gateway/default/node/conf?host&port=/gateway/default/node/conf?host&port)

print('New spark.driver.maxResultSize: ' + sc._conf.get('spark.driver.maxResultSize'))

# Starting  Spark session with configs applied
spark = SparkSession(sc).builder.getOrCreate()

Clean the data, remove stopwords and create index¶

Tokenize the text column and remove stopwords¶

In [12]:
# Add an 'id' column to df: the IDs are not necessarily consecutive but are guaranteed to be unique across the entire DataFrame.
df_text = df_text.withColumn("id", monotonically_increasing_id())

# Split text into words
df_text = df_text.withColumn("words", split(col("text"), " "))

# Remove punctuation and split into words
# \p{P} matches any kind of punctuation character
# \p{C} matches any kind of control character
df_text = df_text.withColumn("clean_text", F.regexp_replace(F.col("text"), "[\p{P}\p{C}]", ""))
df_text = df_text.withColumn("words", split(F.col("clean_text"), " "))

# Filter out tokens that are less than 3 characters
df_text = df_text.withColumn("clean_words", F.expr("filter(words, word -> length(word) > 1)"))

# Remove stopwords
remover = StopWordsRemover(inputCol="clean_words", outputCol="filtered_words")
df_text = remover.transform(df_text)

display(df_text.select('id', 
                       'text', 
                       'clean_text', 
                       'words', 
                       'clean_words', 
                       'filtered_words').limit(5).toPandas())

# Keep only the variables we need
df_text = df_text.select('id','text','filtered_words')

Step 4. Establish similarity threshold and return near-duplicate records¶

Note: we are joining dataframe to itself to get near-duplicate pairs¶

Also note: you do not join on specific variables like keys or IDs. Instead, you join based on the similarity of feature vectors, which is determined using LSH algorithms.

These code use the MinHashLSH model to find pairs of documents with Jaccard similarities above a specified threshold (jaccard_distance). The resulting DataFrame (df_dups_text) contains pairs of similar documents along with their Jaccard distances and text content.

.filter("datasetA.id < datasetB.id"): This line filters out pairs of documents where the ID of the first document (datasetA.id) is less than the ID of the second document (datasetB.id). This ensures that each pair is only considered once, avoiding duplicate comparisons and self-comparisons.

a Jaccard distance of 0.3 means that pairs of sets with a Jaccard similarity (1 - Jaccard distance) greater than or equal to 0.7 will be considered similar.¶

In [16]:
jaccard_distance = 0.3 # the threshold, more strict threshold here

            col("distCol"),
            col("datasetA.id").alias("id_A"),
            col("datasetB.id").alias("id_B"),
            col('datasetA.text').alias('text_A'),
            col('datasetB.text').alias('text_B'),
#             col('datasetA.list_of_words').alias('words_A'),

            )

records = df_hashed_text.count()
# This line counts the total number of records (rows) in the DataFrame df_hashed_text, which contains the hashed text data.

dups = df_dups_text.select('id_A').distinct().count()
# This line counts the number of distinct IDs from the 'id_A' column in the DataFrame df_dups_text. 
# These IDs represent the first document in each pair of similar documents found during the approximate similarity join operation. 
# Counting the distinct IDs gives us the count of unique documents that are found to be similar to at least one other document.

uniques = records - dups

print ('Total records: ', records)
print ('Duplicate titles based on {', jaccard_distance, '} jaccard distance: ', dups)
print ('Unique titles based on {', jaccard_distance, '} jaccard distance: ', jaccard_distance, ': ', uniques)
